Tumelo Mphulo owns a hair salon and employs five people. She has not been able to pay rent or her workers since April. Courtesy #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - Regrowth. Split ends. Bare nails. That's the reality of many consumers who haven't been able to visit the hairdresser or beauty salon in over two months. But, a fight is brewing. The DA is preparing to present arguments in court on Friday to force government to lift the ban on the personal care industry. Tumelo Mphulo owns a hair salon and employs five people. READ: Sit-down restaurants, personal care services could open under level 3 She has not been able to pay rent or her workers since April. She worries this is going to kill her business, her livelihood and those of her employees. “We have not seen an income for about three months. I had made certain preparations for my staff and myself. But, I am telling you, we have run out of savings, I have run out of savings. And unfortunately, the preparations that were made to support us were really not easily reachable and the processes were very long. So, I personally feel that not only have we not had an income but we have been invisible as an industry,” said Mphulo. - Coronavirus Hotline Number: 0800 029 999 from 8am to 4pm, Monday to Friday Help protect your loved ones by sharing this official South African government COVID-19 service with your family, friends and community. Send HI to 0600 123 456 on WhatsApp. The NICD has another Clinician Hotline to improve #COVID19 communication and support for healthcare providers. The Clinician Hotline is 0800 11 1131, operating 24 hrs. The Public Hotline is 0800 029 999 also operating 24hrs.